    <h1>Ankit Bisain's Linux Commands</h1>
	<h2>#1: echo </h2>
	<p>Typing "echo [string]" makes the computer say [string]. This can be used to display the outcome of a function (for example, the state of the rpi in the project).</p>
	<h2>#2: cd </h2>
        <p>Typing "cd [directory]" is used to 'enter' a directory. This is used to access things within folders from the terminal.</p>
	<h2>#3: nano </h2>
        <p>Typing "nano [file]" opens an editor in which you can view and change the file. This is used to change files to write scripts and stuff.</p>   
	<h2>#4: clear </h2>
        <p>Typing "clear" clears all commands and output from the screen. This is typically used for aesthetic reasons.</p>
	<h2>#5: man </h2>
        <p>Typing "man [command]" makes a manual of how to use [command] be displayed. This is used to find out how a command works, as well as ways it can be modified.</p>
	<h2>#6: cat </h2>
        <p>Typing "cat [file]" shows the content of [file]. This is used to conveniently figure out what a file is and what is in it.</p>
	        <h2>#7: ls </h2>
        <p>Typing "ls" lists the current directory. This is used to check which files exist and are currently accessible.</p>
        <h2>#8:mkdir </h2>
        <p>Typing "mkdir [name]" creates a directory with the given name. It is used to create directories to store things.</p> 
<h2>#9: rm </h2>
        <p>Typing "rm [name]" removes the object with the given name. It is used to delete redundant or useless files.</p> 
<h2>#10: scp </h2>
        <p>Typing "scp [file] [location]" copies the file to the location. It is used to move files into places so they can be accessed.</p>

 </body>
